lead_paragraph: SEOUL, Korea — The disclosure a few days ago that the United States Second Infantry Division is going to be withdrawn from its frontline positions in Korea reminded a great many Americans who had forgotten all about it that there is in fact a frontline in Korea and that American troops have formed part of it for more than twenty years. The Korean War came to a halt —though not to an end—in July, 1953; but ever since, that war has been in state of suspended animation with strange life of its own. Along the sta tionary frontline runs an undercurrent of tension; American soldiers confront Communist soldiers; small but bloody encounters occasionally erupt; there are the elements of war without a war.

lead_paragraph: Were this book fiction, it would have been an engrossing yarn of the sea, the intrigue of intelligence, and the perils of a harsh prison in a faraway land. But the story it tells is painfully true. lead_paragraph: Dare one suggest that Korea's Richard Kim—author of the highly acclaimed novel, “The Martyred”—is even better at the “nonfiction novel”? His new book cannot really be called a book of memoirs, because the first episode—in which his parents, in 1933, cross a frozen river into Man churia to escape at least some of the Japanese control—occurs before he is old enough to remember. The fact that he chooses to end his book on the day of the Japanese surrender, before Kim H‐sung and his Commu nist regime assume power in Korea, suggests another way in which it is not quite a memoir. It is too selective, too carefully unified around a single theme or mood.

lead_paragraph: TOKYO, Wednesday, Dec. 9 (UPI)—Gen. Curtis E. LeMay, Chief of Staff of the United States Air Force, who received the Japanese Government's highest decoration to a foreigner and touched off a protest in Parliament, left here today for Korea. General LeMay was honored Monday for his work in developing Japan's postwar air defense force. The Socialists, charging that he helped plan the atomic bomb attacks on Hiroshima and Nagasaki, protested the decoration.
headline.main: LeMay Leaves for Korea

abstract: Korea, S
snippet: Korea, S
lead_paragraph: SEOUL, Korea—For the curious traveler, a visit to Korea Is an exciting experience that lies less than a two‐hour flight from Tokyo. This is a small country, and it is still unspoiled by tourists. The verdant countryside is one giant rice paddy that offers a sharp contrast to the drabness of the capital city of Seoul. Seoul, however, is only architecturally drab. The friendliness of the people, the colorful local costumes worn by both men and women, the unusual food and the gracious royal palaces more than compensate for the outward unattractiveness of this city of more than 3 million. Korea, once called Chosen, has been occupied for many centuries—first by the Chinese, then by the Japanese, later by the Russians and then once again by the Japanese. The continuous occupation by a series of unwelcome invaders caused this small nation to withdraw from the world. Visitors were refused entry, and Korean nationals could not leave their country; in fact, so great was the withdrawal that this became known as the Hermit. Kingdom.

Some persons hope, others despair and everyone waits.

lead_paragraph: Under any circumstances the death of Douglas MacArthur would have been a memorable event in the history of the United Nations.
